{\"video_title\": \"Few-shot Examples for Actions\", \"transcript\": \"вЂ‹Large language models can actually do some planning, вЂ‹which is an interesting ability. вЂ‹They can actually go through and take вЂ‹patterns and with few-shot examples вЂ‹and they can learn what вЂ‹the next action should be given a particular situation. вЂ‹But I'm giving you вЂ‹this example not because they are limited to вЂ‹coming up with planning in the sense of вЂ‹actions or doing sentiment analysis, вЂ‹but I want you to expand вЂ‹your mind on what's possible with вЂ‹few-shot prompting and see it as a technique that вЂ‹can be taken and adapted to all kinds of situations. вЂ‹We've seen how we can use вЂ‹few-shot prompting when we're doing sentiment analysis, вЂ‹now we're going to do something very different with it. вЂ‹We're going to take a look at вЂ‹this example where we're describing вЂ‹different situations with driving a car. вЂ‹In the first one, we see, вЂ‹situation: I'm traveling 60 miles per hour and I see вЂ‹the brake lights on the car in front of me come вЂ‹on and the action is we're going to break. вЂ‹Again, we've got our first example вЂ‹in our few-shot examples. вЂ‹Situation: I've just entered вЂ‹the highway from an on-ramp and I'm вЂ‹traveling 30 miles per hour, action: accelerate. вЂ‹We're teaching вЂ‹the large language model that it's going to вЂ‹be given a situation and it needs to вЂ‹decide what the car should do. вЂ‹Situation: a deer has darted out in front of вЂ‹my car while I'm traveling вЂ‹15 miles per hour and the road has a large shoulder, вЂ‹action: break and swerve into the shoulder. вЂ‹Situation: I'm backing out вЂ‹of a parking spot and I see the reverse lights вЂ‹illuminate on the car behind me and then вЂ‹we prompt it with action. вЂ‹We leave off at the end of our prompt вЂ‹with something that indicates a large language model. вЂ‹We want it to decide what вЂ‹the action is and what do we see it do? вЂ‹It actually says, stop and wait for вЂ‹the car to back out before proceeding вЂ‹and it's making a sensible decision вЂ‹about what the action should be. вЂ‹Now, I don't think we should go and build вЂ‹self-driving cars with few-shot prompting. вЂ‹I don't think we're going to get there with that, вЂ‹but I do want to show you that we don't вЂ‹have to think just with a narrow, вЂ‹rigid box of classify something. вЂ‹We can actually have вЂ‹complex tasks that we're having to perform. вЂ‹Now sentiment analysis is a complex task, вЂ‹but this is also a very complex task, вЂ‹it's in a different vein. вЂ‹I want us to think very вЂ‹creatively about how we can use few-shot prompts. вЂ‹Now again, one of the things that we're вЂ‹getting is we're getting some constraints on our output. вЂ‹It's learning what the output should look like. вЂ‹Now, I'm going to then вЂ‹go and do something else interesting. вЂ‹I'm going to show you an interesting capability вЂ‹of large language models. вЂ‹One of the things that can be done to вЂ‹use one large language model to teach another one, вЂ‹which is an interesting capability. вЂ‹I'm going to say, вЂ‹please provide more examples, вЂ‹and then I'm going to prompt it with situation. вЂ‹It's going to start generating вЂ‹additional situations and actions. вЂ‹It's learned from our pattern, вЂ‹the types of things that we're вЂ‹describing and the types of вЂ‹actions and now it's вЂ‹going to go and generate more example. вЂ‹It says, you are driving in вЂ‹heavy rain and notice that the road ahead is flooded, вЂ‹so this is the continuation of our situation. вЂ‹Then it says, action: slow вЂ‹down and cautiously drive through the flooded area, вЂ‹watching out for other vehicles and вЂ‹avoiding sudden movements or changes in directions. вЂ‹I would actually disagree with this. вЂ‹I'm not sure that it's вЂ‹smart to drive through a flooded area. вЂ‹That's probably questionable decision-making, вЂ‹which again, вЂ‹just reminds you that you need to own вЂ‹the output of a large language model and check it. вЂ‹Situation: you are driving on a two lane road and вЂ‹a car is approaching you from вЂ‹the opposite direction with their high beams on, вЂ‹action: dim your headlights to вЂ‹low beams to avoid blinding the oncoming driver. вЂ‹But you notice the interesting thing вЂ‹about this is it's giving us вЂ‹some rich situations and possibly appropriate actions. вЂ‹I'm not sure I agree with the flooded one, вЂ‹but we're generating different examples вЂ‹of situations and what to вЂ‹do and they look very similar to what we produced before. вЂ‹One thing that's interesting is we can вЂ‹actually take examples like вЂ‹this and then curate them and have a human edit them, вЂ‹and then provide them back вЂ‹to a large language model either вЂ‹later as additional examples for our few-shot examples. вЂ‹Once we've had a human look вЂ‹at them and curate them a little bit, вЂ‹maybe clean them up, вЂ‹maybe we don't want that one on вЂ‹flooding because we don't think that's a good idea, вЂ‹so we actually say, well, вЂ‹you shouldn't drive across flooding, вЂ‹we spell the rules. вЂ‹But you can imagine that the level of effort вЂ‹to create the initial examples right вЂ‹here is much higher than the effort to go through and вЂ‹generate subsequent examples which вЂ‹we can then go and hand edit and curate, вЂ‹so we can quickly build up these examples, вЂ‹both in order to вЂ‹generate an output right now that we want, вЂ‹but also to generate examples that we can later вЂ‹give back to the same large language model, вЂ‹or that we could go and give to вЂ‹another large language model to teach it. вЂ‹In fact, some people have actually gone and done this. вЂ‹They've taken output from ChatGPT, вЂ‹for example, and they've taken it вЂ‹into another large language model, вЂ‹like Facebook's LLaMA, вЂ‹and used the output from вЂ‹ChatGPT to improve the outputs of LLaMA. вЂ‹This is another interesting capability, вЂ‹is that large language models, вЂ‹through these few-shot examples, вЂ‹they can generate few-shot examples for other models. вЂ